{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522537"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:46:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:46:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13836"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13836"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.02,0.2,0.33,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50437"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6453"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35659"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14201"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50437"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with progressive shortness of breath over the past 24 hours. She has a history of end-stage kidney disease and missed her last scheduled haemodialysis session. She is anuric at baseline. On examination, she appears distressed with a respiratory rate of 30/min, pulse rate 110/min, blood pressure 180/95 mmHg, SpO2 86% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She is alert and oriented. Chest auscultation reveals bibasal crepitations. The only finding of significance on ECG is sinus tachycardia. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EpH: 7.25 (7.35-7.45)\u003Cbr /\u003EUrea: 21.0 mmol/L (3.0-10.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EBicarbonate: 16 mmol/L (22-28)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 680 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most urgent emergency indication for dialysis in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperkalaemia","Hypertension","Creatinine greater than 500 \u00b5mol/L","Fluid overload","Metabolic acidosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple complications of a missed haemodialysis session, including metabolic acidosis, hyperkalaemia and fluid overload. Among the options provided, \u003Cstrong\u003Efluid overload\u003C/strong\u003E is the most urgent indication for emergency dialysis, given the patient is in respiratory distress, with tachypnoea, hypoxia and clinical evidence of pulmonary oedema. Given the patient is anuric at baseline, diuretics will not be effective as a temporising or definitive measure in offloading fluid. If left untreated, this patient is likely to deteriorate from a respiratory perspective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Emetabolic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is present (pH 7.25, bicarbonate 16 mmol/L), it is not as immediately life-threatening as the fluid overload causing hypoxia. However, if the acidosis were more severe (pH \u0026lt;7.1) and refractory to medical management, it would also be an indication for emergency dialysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperkalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is present (K 5.2), it is mild and not as immediately life-threatening as the fluid overload causing hypoxia. There are no ECG changes of hyperkalaemia. However, if the hyperkalaemia was more severe and refractory to medical management, it would also be an indication for emergency dialysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E in this patient is likely in the context of fluid overload. Whilst elevated, raised blood pressure in itself is not an indication for emergency dialysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreatinine greater than 500 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/strong\u003E is an arbitrary criterion and not an indication for emergency dialysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The acute indications for emergency dialysis are refractory metabolic acidosis, refractory electrolyte disturbances (i.e. hyperkalaemia), intoxicants/toxins, refractory fluid overload, and symptomatic uraemia. These can be remembered with the mnemonic: AEIOU."],"references":["Murdeshwar HN, Anjum F. Hemodialysis [Internet]. PubMed. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563296/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35659"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13836"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35659"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-11T23:15:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-11T23:15:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6453"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50437"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadin